AUJESZKY'S DISEASE - FRANCE: (MEUSE) CANINE
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 14 Jan 2014
Source: Estrepublicain.fr [in French, trans. Corr.SB, summ., edited]
http://www.estrepublicain.fr/actualite/2014/01/14/meuse-trois-cas-de-maladie-d-aujesky-sur-des-chiens-de-chasse


The prefecture of Meuse warned in a statement that 3 cases of Aujeszky's disease (AD) were confirmed in late 2013 in hunting dogs who had been in contact with wild boars in the communes of Loisey and Sommedieue.

This disease is caused by a herpesvirus that invades the domestic pig and wild boar but less frequently may be transmitted to other species such as carnivores, ruminants, and equines. This disease is not transmissible to humans.

Carnivores can be infected by ingesting offal and uncooked meat of pigs or wild boar, by a bite, or direct contact, such as during a hunt.

The predominant clinical signs in dogs are those of encephalomyelitis, paralysis of the larynx, and significant pruritus, which may lead the animal to harm itself. Incubation lasts from 2 to 6 days and death is rapid, within 48 hours after onset of symptoms. There is no treatment.

Protective measures that can be considered for dogs are the limiting of contact with wild boars and refraining from feeding them with offal or uncooked (pig) meat.

The prefecture of Meuse states that any owner whose dog(s) have symptoms of this disease should contact their veterinarian or the Departmental Directorate of Social Cohesion and Protection of the Population (DDCSPP), Meuse (Tel. 03 29 77 42 00).

