[Aujeszky's disease (AD), also known as pseudorabies, is included in OIE's list of reportable diseases (multi-species group).

AD is caused by an alphaherpesvirus that infects the central nervous system and other organs, such as the respiratory tract, of various mammals (such as dogs, cats, cattle, sheep, rabbits, foxes, minks) except humans and the tailless apes. It is associated primarily with pigs, the natural hosts, which remain latently infected following clinical recovery (except piglets under 2 weeks old, which die from encephalitis). In consequence, the pig is the only species able to survive a productive infection and therefore, serves as the reservoir host. In pigs, the severity of clinical signs depends on the age of the pig, the route of infection, the virulence of the infecting strain, and the immunological status of the animal. Young piglets are highly susceptible with mortality rates reaching 100 per cent during the 1st 2 weeks of age. When pigs are older than 2 months (grower-finisher pigs), the respiratory forms become predominant with hyperthermia, anorexia, and mild to severe respiratory signs. In other species, AD is less common. In cattle and sheep, it is almost always fatal within a few days, clinically resembling scrapie: the 1st symptom is intense pruritus concentrated in a patch of skin, usually manifested as severe licking, rubbing, or gnawing. Affected animals become progressively weaker, and eventually recumbent. Convulsions, bellowing, teeth grinding, cardiac irregularities, and rapid, shallow breathing are common. The clinical signs are similar in dogs and cats, and a combination of neurologic signs, pharyngeal paralysis, and profuse salivation may resemble rabies. Affected animals typically die within 1 to 2 days.

A diagnosis of Aujeszky's disease is established by detecting the agent (virus isolation, polymerase chain reaction [PCR]), as well as by detecting a serological response in the live animal.

Aujeszky's disease is endemic in many parts of the world, but several countries, such as the USA, Canada, New Zealand, and many member states of the European Union, have successfully completed eradication programmes.

The above and additional information on AD is available in OIE's relevant manual chapter, at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.01.02_AUJESZKYS_DIS.pdf and in http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/aujeszkys_disease.pdf.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of France can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/9PgU. The department of Meuse is located in the Lorraine Region, in north east France; it can be seen on the map at http://www.trussel.com/maig/image/frdeptb.jpg. - Mod.AS]
